2. Define a variable for the character's current velocity and acceleration.
3. In the Update() method, calculate the character's new position based on its current velocity and acceleration.
4. Apply a force to the character's Rigidbody to make it move in the calculated direction.
5. Add a drag force to slow down the character's movement over time.
6. Use the FixedUpdate() method to update the character's position and velocity.

Here's an example of how you could implement this in C#:
```
public class Inertia Movement : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float speed = 10.0f;
    public float acceleration = 5.0f;
    public float drag = 0.1f;

    private Rigidbody rb;
    private Vector3 velocity = Vector3.zero;

    void Start()
    {
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
    }

    void FixedUpdate()
    {
        // Calculate new velocity
        velocity += acceleration * Time.deltaTime;

        // Apply drag
        velocity *= Mathf.Lerp(1.0f, 0.0f, drag * Time.deltaTime);

        // Calculate new position
        float moveHorizontal = velocity.x * Time.deltaTime;
        float moveVertical = velocity.z * Time.deltaTime;
        float moveForward = velocity.y * Time.deltaTime;

        // Move the character
        rb.position += new Vector3(moveHorizontal, 0, moveVertical);

        // Apply force in the direction of movement
        rb.AddForce(Vector3.normalize(velocity) * speed, ForceMode.Impulse);
    }
}
```
This script will make your character move in the direction of its current velocity, and slow down over time due to the drag force. You can adjust the `speed`, `acceleration`, and `drag` variables to fine-tune the movement behavior.

