### PHP Code to Handle Form Submission

After the form is submitted, you can check if the checkbox was checked by checking if the `switch_status` variable is set in the `$_POST` array. If it is set, it means the checkbox was checked; otherwise, it was not.

Heres an example of how you can handle this in your PHP code:

```php
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST' && isset($_GET['sent'])) {
    // Get the values from the form
    $user = $_POST['user'];
    $numero = $_POST['numero'];
    $date = $_POST['date'];
    $time = $_POST['time'];
    $radiogroup = $_POST['radiogroup'];
    $alert = $_POST['alert'];
    $message = $_POST['message'];

    // Check if the switch is checked
    $switch_status = isset($_POST['switch_status']) ? true : false;

    // Now you can use $switch_status to determine if the checkbox was checked
    if ($switch_status) {
        // Checkbox is checked
        echo "The switch is ON.";
    } else {
        // Checkbox is not checked
        echo "The switch is OFF.";
    }

    // Continue processing the rest of the form data...
}
```

### Summary

1. **Add a `name` attribute** to the checkbox input to make it accessible in the `$_POST` array.
2. **Check for the checkbox state** in your PHP code after form submission using `isset($_POST['switch_status'])`.

With these changes, you will be able to determine whether the checkbox was checked or not when the form is submitted.

